   Municipals
                                                                                                       

   Advancing to mostly unchanged levels after slim declines
on new economic data, municipal bonds were flat to up 1/8
point in thin late trading.
   New Jersey Turnpike Authority's 7.20% issue of 2018 was
unchanged at 98 bid to yield 7.36%.
   Some municipal issues had traded down about 1/8 point
after the release of the Chicago Purchasing Management
Association's index for May, traders said.
   In addition, news that President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev may agree on the major elements of a
strategic arms reduction treaty today, buoyed the market,
some traders said.
   In slim new issue dealings, a $50.9 million issue of New
Jersey certificates of participation was won by a Dillon,
Read &amp; Co. group. The bonds were priced to yield from 5.90%
in 1990 to 6.65% in 1997.
   No large municipal issues are expected to be priced today.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Japanese government bonds ended stronger on news that
Japanese wholesale prices declined.
   The Japanese government said wholesale prices fell 0.4% in
the second 10 days of May from the first 10 days. Traders
said most buyers Thursday were dealers.
   The price of Japan's benchmark 10-year government security
rose to 88.14 points to yield 6.94%. (The yield is calculated
in local terms, but it would be 6.56% if calculated by the
semiannual compound measure used in the U.S.)
   In Britain, government bonds ended moderately lower as
speculation faded again about an imminent entry by Britain
into the European Monetary System's exchange rate mechanism.
   Prices had surged Wednesday on renewed speculation that
British authorities were about to make an announcement
concerning the mechanism, which is the European Community's
currency stabilization arrangement. But in comments made on
Wednesday, Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major didn't say
anything regarding the country's entry into the arrangement.
   In Frankfurt, West German Bundesbank President Karl Otto
Poehl also discouraged expectations. He said "Britain can't
and shouldn't participate in the EMS" because of its high
inflation and balance-of-payment problems.
   Britain's 11 3/4% bond due 2003/2007 fell 9/32 to 99 27/32
to yield 11.76%.
